1:52 So, those aren't fossils, those are petrified bones from a plasma storm which causes instant petrification. We have that in Australia where a recent tree was struck by lightning and turned into stone. Same with crabs and seashells on the ocean shore. A day earlier, they were alive, the next day, they are turned to stone/sodium carbonate. A fossil is only an imprint, you never say that bones are a fossil. What you have there are bones, but bones will decompose as they are organic matter. The only reason they still exist is because they are no longer bones, but petrified bones. Petrification is the process of something being converted to stone. Bones decompose too fast for it to occur the slow way, the only way it happens is via plasma storm discharge.
